{"key":"processedPost-18943899","value":{"id":18943899,"first":9868174,"last":18953568,"when":1381160144,"utime":"10/07/13 06:35 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>eelrd72 said:</strong><br />I will take and set a couple of dishes in front of it with the lids off and put lid back. If they come up clean. I will know the flowhood is good.</blockquote><br />As has been posted here hundreds of times, that isn't a valid test.&nbsp; The best flowhoods are 99.99% efficient, which means if there's a few billion contaminants floating around, thousands of them are going to make it through.&nbsp; This is why we should never have the lid off a petri dish for over 5 seconds. . .ever.<br />However, even more important is to <i>never, I repeat never open a contaminated petri dish in front of a flow hood. </i> That just blows the spores everywhere.&nbsp; Always work from contaminated dishes in a glove or still air box.<br />RR","title":"Re: bacteria with my flowhood"}}